This paper deals with the topic of compress-forward relaying in communication networks, which is a subfield of information theory (cs.IT). It also involves the use of relay channels (cs.NI) and the analysis of achievable rate regions (cs.SI). The paper also discusses the impact of Wyner-Ziv binning on the performance of compress-forward relaying, which is related to coding and error correction (cs.CE). Finally, the paper mentions the use of compress-forward relaying in certain Gaussian channel configurations, which could be considered a subfield of multimedia communication (cs.MM).
